==Partial reveal==
Some commitment schemes permit a proof to be given of only a portion of the committed value. In these schemes, the secret value formula_54 is a vector of many individually separable values.
:formula_55
The commitment formula_56 is computed from formula_54 in the commit phase. Normally, in the reveal phase, the prover would reveal all of formula_54 and some additional proof data (such as formula_59 in simple bit-commitment). Instead, the prover is able to reveal any single value from the formula_54 vector, and create an efficient proof that it is the authentic formula_61th element of the original vector that created the commitment formula_56. The proof does not require any values of formula_54 other than formula_64 to be revealed, and it is impossible to create valid proofs that reveal different values for any of the formula_64 than the true one.

===Vector hashing===

Vector hashing is a naive vector commitment partial reveal scheme based on bit-commitment. Values formula_66 are chosen randomly. Individual commitments are created by hashing formula_67. The overall commitment is computed as
:formula_68
In order to prove one element of the vector formula_54, the prover reveals the values
:formula_70
The verifier is able to compute formula_71 from formula_64 and formula_73, and then is able to verify that the hash of all formula_74 values is the commitment formula_56. 
Unfortunately the proof is formula_76 in size and verification time. Alternately, if formula_56 is the set of all formula_74 values, then the commitment is formula_76 in size, and the proof is formula_80 in size and verification time. Either way, the commitment or the proof scales with formula_76 which is not optimal.

===Merkle tree===
A common example of a practical partial reveal scheme is a Merkle tree, in which a binary hash tree is created of the elements of formula_54. This scheme creates commitments that are formula_80 in size, and proofs that are formula_84 in size and verification time. The root hash of the tree is the commitment formula_56. To prove that a revealed formula_64 is part of the original tree, only formula_87 hash values from the tree, one from each level, must be revealed as the proof. The verifier is able to follow the path from the claimed leaf node all the way up to the root, hashing in the sibling nodes at each level, and eventually arriving at a root node value that must equal formula_56.

===KZG commitment===
A Kate-Zaverucha-Goldberg commitment uses pairing-based cryptography to build a partial reveal scheme with formula_80 commitment sizes, proof sizes, and proof verification time. In other words, as formula_90, the number of values in formula_54, increases, the commitments and proofs do not get larger, and the proofs do not take any more effort to verify.

A KZG commitment requires a predetermined set of parameters to create a pairing, and a trusted trapdoor element. For example, a Tate pairing can be used. Assume that formula_92 are the additive groups, and formula_93 is the multiplicative group of the pairing. In other words, the pairing is the map formula_94. Let formula_95 be the trapdoor element (if formula_24 is the prime order of formula_97 and formula_98), and let formula_99 and formula_100 be the generators of formula_97 and formula_98 respectively. As part of the parameter setup, we assume that formula_103 and formula_104 are known and shared values for arbitrarily many positive integer values of formula_61, while the trapdoor value formula_106 itself is discarded and known to no one.

====Commit====

A KZG commitment reformulates the vector of values to be committed as a polynomial. First, we calculate a polynomial such that formula_107 for all values of formula_64 in our vector. Lagrange interpolation allows us to compute that polynomial
